## CODING CONVENTIONS — FOLLOW THESE EXACTLY

### TypeScript
- Strict mode always — no `any` types
- Define all interfaces in `types/index.ts`
- Use `type` for unions, `interface` for objects
- Always handle null/undefined explicitly

### Naming
- Files: kebab-case (`product-capture.ts`)
- Components: PascalCase (`StyleProfile.tsx`)
- Functions: camelCase (`capturePageView`)
- Constants: SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE (`MAX_DWELL_MS`)
- Database columns: snake_case (`shopper_id`, `event_type`)
- TypeScript types: PascalCase (`ProductData`, `ShopperSignal`)

### Extension-specific rules
- Never use `document.cookie` — no cookie access
- Never capture data outside fashion site matches
- Always use `chrome.storage.local` not `localStorage`
- Always check if on a product page before firing events
- Throttle all scroll and mutation observers — never fire on every pixel
- SPA navigation detection is mandatory — use MutationObserver on document.body
- Always send events through background.ts, never directly from content script

### Error handling
- Never let extension errors surface to the user
- Wrap all content script logic in try/catch
- Log errors to chrome.storage.local for debugging, not console.error in production
- API failures must not block the UI — fail silently and queue for retry

### Privacy
- Extension only runs on whitelisted fashion site domains
- No data captured outside product pages
- No cookies, no fingerprinting
- Only capture fashion-relevant signals — never intercept unrelated network requests
- Never log personally identifiable information to console

### Environment variables in Plasmo
- Use `process.env.PLASMO_PUBLIC_*` prefix for variables exposed to content scripts
- Never expose API keys in content scripts

